ASP.NET Core MVC is a cross-platform, open-source framework for building modern, cloud-ready, and testable web applications. It combines the Model-View-Controller (MVC) design pattern with the flexibility of ASP.NET Core’s modular architecture.

🔑 Key Features
Cross-platform: Runs on Windows, Linux, macOS.

Unified framework: Merges MVC, Web API, and Razor Pages under ASP.NET Core.

Middleware pipeline: Request handling is modular via middleware components.

Dependency Injection (DI): Built-in DI container for loose coupling.

Routing: Attribute routing and conventional routing supported.

Tag Helpers: Server-side helpers that make Razor views more HTML-friendly.

Configuration system: Strongly typed, environment-based configuration.

Security: Identity, authentication, authorization, anti-forgery tokens.

Performance: Lightweight, faster than traditional ASP.NET due to Kestrel server and modular design.

Testing: Supports unit testing and integration testing with ease.

⚙️ MVC Pattern
Model: Represents application data and business logic.

View: UI layer, typically Razor views.

Controller: Handles requests, interacts with models, and returns views or data.

🚀 Request Lifecycle
Request enters via Kestrel web server.

Passes through middleware pipeline (authentication, routing, etc.).

Routed to a controller action.

Action interacts with model/services.

Returns a view or JSON response.

Response flows back through middleware to the client.

🛠️ Common Use Cases
Building RESTful APIs.

Creating dynamic web applications with Razor views.

Integrating with client-side frameworks (Angular, React).

Enterprise apps requiring modularity, scalability, and testability.

🎯 25 ASP.NET Core MVC Interview Q&A
1. What is ASP.NET Core MVC?
ASP.NET Core MVC is a framework for building web apps using the MVC pattern. Unlike classic ASP.NET MVC, it’s cross-platform, modular, and integrates Web API and Razor Pages. It emphasizes performance and testability.

2. Difference between ASP.NET MVC and ASP.NET Core MVC?
ASP.NET MVC: Windows-only, tightly coupled with System.Web, heavier.

ASP.NET Core MVC: Cross-platform, lightweight, modular, uses middleware, integrates Web API.

3. Explain the MVC pattern.
Model: Business logic/data.

View: UI presentation.

Controller: Request handler, orchestrates between model and view.

4. What is Middleware in ASP.NET Core?
Middleware are components in the request pipeline that process requests/responses. Examples: Authentication, Routing, Static Files. They replace HttpModules/HttpHandlers from classic ASP.NET.

5. How does Routing work in ASP.NET Core MVC?
Routing maps incoming requests to controller actions. Two types:

Conventional routing: Defined in Program.cs or Startup.cs.

Attribute routing: Decorates controllers/actions with [Route].

6. What are Tag Helpers?
Tag Helpers are server-side components that let you write Razor views with HTML-like syntax. Example: <form asp-action="Login">.

7. Explain Dependency Injection in ASP.NET Core.
ASP.NET Core has built-in DI. Services are registered in Program.cs (builder.Services.AddScoped<>()) and injected into controllers via constructors.

8. What is Kestrel?
Kestrel is the default cross-platform web server for ASP.NET Core. It’s lightweight, fast, and can run standalone or behind IIS/NGINX.

9. What is the difference between ViewData, ViewBag, and TempData?
ViewData: Dictionary, weakly typed.

ViewBag: Dynamic wrapper around ViewData.

TempData: Stores data for one request, survives redirects.

10. What are Filters in ASP.NET Core MVC?
Filters allow code execution before/after controller actions. Types: Authorization, Resource, Action, Exception, Result filters.

11. Explain Model Binding.
Model binding maps HTTP request data (query string, form data, route values) to action method parameters automatically.

12. What is Razor?
Razor is a view engine that allows embedding C# code in HTML using @ syntax. Example: @Model.Name.

13. What is the difference between Razor Pages and MVC?
Razor Pages: Page-focused, simpler for small apps.

MVC: Controller-focused, better for large apps with complex routing.

14. How is Configuration handled in ASP.NET Core?
Configuration is environment-based, supports JSON, XML, environment variables, and strongly typed options via IOptions<T>.

15. Explain Authentication vs Authorization.
Authentication: Verifying identity (login).

Authorization: Granting access to resources based on roles/policies.

16. What is ASP.NET Core Identity?
Identity is a membership system for authentication/authorization. Provides user management, roles, claims, and token support.

17. Explain ActionResult vs IActionResult.
ActionResult: Base class for returning views, JSON, etc.

IActionResult: Interface, more flexible, allows custom implementations.

18. What is the difference between Partial View and Layout View?
Layout View: Defines common structure (header, footer).

Partial View: Reusable view snippet (like a widget).

19. What is Anti-forgery Token?
Security feature to prevent CSRF attacks. Implemented via @Html.AntiForgeryToken() and validated by middleware.

20. Explain REST API in ASP.NET Core MVC.
ASP.NET Core MVC supports building REST APIs using controllers with [ApiController] and returning JSON responses.

21. What is the Startup.cs / Program.cs role?
Defines the app’s request pipeline and service configuration. In .NET 6+, Program.cs uses minimal hosting model.

22. What is the difference between AddScoped, AddTransient, AddSingleton?
Scoped: One instance per request.

Transient: New instance every time.

Singleton: One instance for the entire app lifetime.

23. Explain Exception Handling in ASP.NET Core.
Handled via middleware (UseExceptionHandler, UseDeveloperExceptionPage) or filters. Can log and return custom error responses.

24. What is the difference between IActionFilter and IResultFilter?
IActionFilter: Runs before/after action methods.

IResultFilter: Runs before/after action results (views, JSON).

25. How do you secure an ASP.NET Core MVC application?
Use HTTPS.

Implement Identity/Authentication.

Apply Authorization policies.

Use Anti-forgery tokens.

Validate input to prevent SQL injection/XSS.
